    summary: "A Member of Parliament in the Lok Sabha (the \"House of the People\", India's lower house) is directly elected by voters of one parliamentary constituency for a term of up to five years — though the House can be dissolved earlier (Constitution, Articles 81 and 83). Their job has three main parts: making laws — they debate and vote on Bills on Union and Concurrent List subjects; controlling the public purse — they approve the Union Budget, taxes and spending, and Money Bills can only start in the Lok Sabha (Articles 109–110); and checking the government — through Question Hour, Zero Hour, debates, motions, and parliamentary committees. Only the Lok Sabha can bring down the government through a no-confidence motion. An MP also represents their constituency: raising local concerns with central ministries, helping with grievances, and recommending local works under the MPLAD Scheme (about ₹5 crore a year, restricted to recommending — actual work is executed by the district administration). An MP is NOT a mayor, MLA, or police chief: everyday civic services, state schemes, and law-and-order are handled by local bodies and the state government. Unless the MP is also a Union Minister, they do not run any government department. Their salary, allowances and pension come under the Salary, Allowances and Pension of Members of Parliament Act, 1954, and they must file a truthful election affidavit (assets, liabilities, criminal cases) with the Election Commission and follow the anti-defection rules of the Tenth Schedule.",
