    oneLine: "A Member of Parliament in the Rajya Sabha helps make national laws for the whole country and speaks up for their state, but is chosen by the state's elected MLAs (or nominated by the President) rather than by voters directly.",
    summary: "The Rajya Sabha (Council of States) is the upper house of India's Parliament (Article 80). Most of its members represent a State or Union Territory and are elected by the elected members of that State's Legislative Assembly (or, for a Union Territory that has a legislature, by a special electoral college), using proportional representation with a single transferable vote; 12 members are nominated by the President for special knowledge or experience in literature, science, art, or social service. A Rajya Sabha MP serves a six-year term, and one-third of members retire every two years — the House is a permanent, continuing chamber that is never dissolved (Article 83). Their core job is to debate and pass national laws, scrutinise the government through questions and committees, examine the Union Budget, and represent the interests of their State in national law-making. The Rajya Sabha also holds special powers the Lok Sabha does not: it can empower Parliament to legislate on a State List subject in the national interest (Article 249) and to create new All-India Services (Article 312), each needing a resolution passed by at least two-thirds of the members present and voting. On money bills, the Rajya Sabha can only suggest changes within 14 days and cannot block them (Article 109), and it does not vote to remove the government through no-confidence motions — that power belongs only to the Lok Sabha. Like Lok Sabha MPs, each Rajya Sabha MP receives an MPLADS entitlement of Rs 5 crore per year (the scheme was suspended in 2020 during the COVID-19 pandemic and restored from November 2021, and is funded up to 2025-26) to recommend local development works — a Rajya Sabha MP can recommend works in one or more districts within their State, while nominated MPs can recommend works anywhere in the country. Citizens can hold a Rajya Sabha MP to account for attending and participating in the House, using their powers and MPLADS entitlement honestly and effectively, disclosing assets and interests, following the law and the rules of the House, behaving ethically, and being reachable. They are NOT the local municipal or panchayat authority, are not in charge of police or day-to-day state administration, and — unless they also hold a ministerial post — do not run any government department.",
