    summary: "The Prime Minister is the head of the Union (central) government and the real head of India's day-to-day executive, while the President is the ceremonial head of State. A person becomes PM when they can command the confidence (majority support) of the Lok Sabha, the directly elected House; the President then appoints them (Article 75), and the new government must prove that majority on the floor of the House. The PM leads the Council of Ministers, which \"aids and advises\" the President (Article 74), and this whole team is collectively responsible to the Lok Sabha — if it loses the House's confidence, the government must resign. The PM is also the main channel between the Council and the President, with a constitutional duty to keep the President informed of all Union decisions (Article 78). The PM must be, or within six months become, a member of either House of Parliament. This profile covers the Union PM only; each State has its own elected government led by a Chief Minister, and Union Territories are run partly by the Centre through a Lieutenant Governor or Administrator — so many everyday services depend on the State (or UT), not the PM.",
